QueryText: how to manage red opening of bolls ?
KCCAns: In the North Indian situation, shifting of sowing date to late May or June brings about considerable reduction in the incidence of Tirak disorder.The shifting of sowing date enables the curtailment of vegetative growth and enables the crop to overcome the problem of Nitrogen deficiency or non availability of moisture at the time of fruiting.Restoring frequent irrigations to retard development of sub-soil salinity or alkalinity.Applying the proper correctives for nitrogen enrichment especially in the light sandy soil.Use of growth retardants to check excessive vegetative growth and thereby reduce the crop demand for more moisture and nitrogen during the boll development stage.

QueryText: farmer want to know information about WATER MANAGEMENT in wheat?
KCCAns:
recommended for The crop requires 4 - 6 irrigations depending on the soil type and rainfall. Wheat crop requires minimum of 5 irrigations at the following critical stages.
I – Immediately after sowing
II – Crown root intiation : 15-20 DAS 
III- Active tillering stage : 35-40 DAS
IV- Flowering stage : 50-55 DAS
V- Grain filling stage : 70-75 DAS
Crown root initiation and flowering are the most critical stages. Water stagnation should be voided at the time of germination.
